    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Big Tobacco, Duly Punished?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Arpan Dasgupta letter on July 15 article and editorial hails Florida damage award against tobacco companies</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Tobacco Lawsuit in Florida Yields Record Damages'' (front page, July 15) and ''Cigarette Makers Under Siege'' (editorial, July 15):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Tobacco Lawsuit in Florida Yields Record Damages'' (front page, July 15) and ''Cigarette Makers Under Siege'' (editorial, July 15):</p>
        <p>For years, the tobacco companies continued to push their hazardous product to people even when scientific evidence pointed to the fact that nicotine was addictive and cigarettes were a potential carcinogen. Even worse, the industry aimed its product at young people, who were more impressionable.</p>
        <p>Although it may take years for the case to be resolved, I applaud the Florida jury's decision to make the tobacco industry accountable for its products. Professionals like doctors, drivers and pilots are accountable for their actions. The tobacco industry should be no different, especially when it knew the consequences of the use of its product.</p>
        <p>ARPAN DASGUPTA  Highland Park, N.J., July 15, 2000</p>
      </block>
